<chapter subject="Chemistry" id="207" name="Redox Reactions">
    <easy>
        <question>
            <text>Process of addition of oxygen or removal of hydrogen is classical ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Oxidation</option><option id="B">Reduction</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Traditional view of chemical change.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Process of addition of hydrogen or removal of oxygen is classical ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Reduction</option><option id="B">Oxidation</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Traditional view reciprocal.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Loss of electrons by an atom or ion is called ____ (Modern view).</text>
            <option id="A">Oxidation</option><option id="B">Reduction</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>OIL: Oxidation Is Loss.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Gain of electrons by an atom or ion is called ____ (Modern view).</text>
            <option id="A">Reduction</option><option id="B">Oxidation</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>RIG: Reduction Is Gain.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reactions involving simultaneous oxidation and reduction are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Redox</option><option id="B">Acid-Base</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Short for reduction-oxidation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Substance that brings about oxidation and itself gets reduced is ____ agent.</text>
            <option id="A">Oxidizing</option><option id="B">Reducing</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Electron acceptor.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Substance that brings about reduction and itself gets oxidized is ____ agent.</text>
            <option id="A">Reducing</option><option id="B">Oxidizing</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Electron donor.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Apparent charge assigned to an atom in a molecule by following arbitrary rules is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Oxidation Number (O.N.)</option><option id="B">Valency</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Helps in balancing redox reactions.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Oxidation number of all elements in their elementary state is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Zero</option><option id="B">Positive</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Na, H2, S8, P4 = 0.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The algebraic sum of oxidation numbers of all atoms in a neutral molecule is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Zero</option><option id="B">Charged</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Used to find unknown O.N.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Oxidation number of Fluorine is always ____ in its compounds.</text>
            <option id="A">-1</option><option id="B">+1</option><option id="C">0</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Most electronegative element.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Oxidation number of Oxygen is usually ____ except in peroxides and OF2.</text>
            <option id="A">-2</option><option id="B">-1</option><option id="C">+2</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Common value in oxides.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Oxidation number of Oxygen in H2O2 (Peroxide) is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">-1</option><option id="B">-2</option><option id="C">0</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Contains O-O single bond.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Oxidation number of Hydrogen is ____ with non-metals and ____ with active metals (hydrides).</text>
            <option id="A">+1 , -1</option><option id="B">-1, +1</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>More EN than Li but less than Cl.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Oxidation number of Alkali metals in compounds is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">+1</option><option id="B">+2</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Group 1 elements.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Oxidation number of Alkaline Earth metals in compounds is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">+2</option><option id="B">+1</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Group 2 elements.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Oxidation process involves ____ in oxidation number.</text>
            <option id="A">Increase</option><option id="B">Decrease</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Loss of negative electrons makes it more positive.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reduction process involves ____ in oxidation number.</text>
            <option id="A">Decrease</option><option id="B">Increase</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Gain of negative electrons reduces state.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Method for balancing redox by splitting into two parts is ____ method.</text>
            <option id="A">Half-reaction / Ion-electron</option><option id="B">Oxidation state</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Clear step-by-step approach.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Salt bridge in electrochemical cell maintains electrical ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Neutrality</option><option id="B">Pressure</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Allows ion flow between half-cells.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Anode is the electrode where ____ takes place.</text>
            <option id="A">Oxidation</option><option id="B">Reduction</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Target for anions.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Cathode is the electrode where ____ takes place.</text>
            <option id="A">Reduction</option><option id="B">Oxidation</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Target for cations.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A device that converts chemical energy of redox into electrical is ____ cell.</text>
            <option id="A">Galvanic / Voltaic</option><option id="B">Electrolytic</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Daniell Cell.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A device that uses electrical energy to carry out non-spontaneous redox is ____ cell.</text>
            <option id="A">Electrolytic</option><option id="B">Galvanic</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Water electrolysis.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Tendency of an electrode to lose or gain electrons is electrode ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Potential (E)</option><option id="B">Capacity</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Measured relative to reference.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The potential of Standard Hydrogen Electrode (SHE) is assigned as ____ V.</text>
            <option id="A">0.00</option><option id="B">1.00</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Reference zero for the whole series.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The list of electrodes in increasing order of reduction potential is ____ series.</text>
            <option id="A">Electrochemical</option><option id="B">Activity</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Determines viability of redox reactions.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Strongest reducing agent (on top of series, most negative E°) is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Lithium</option><option id="B">Fluorine</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Most reactive metal, easily oxidized.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Strongest oxidizing agent (most positive E°) is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Fluorine</option><option id="B">Lithium</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Highest affinity for electrons.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Standard EMF of cell E°_cell = E°_cathode - ____.</text>
            <option id="A">E°_anode</option><option id="B">E°_cell</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Right electrode - Left electrode potential.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Metals which can displace H2 from dilute acids have ____ reduction potential.</text>
            <option id="A">Negative</option><option id="B">Positive</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Active metals like Zn, Mg.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Noble metals like Gold and Platinum have ____ reduction potential.</text>
            <option id="A">High Positive</option><option id="B">Highly Negative</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Highly resistant to oxidation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>In Daniell cell, Zinc acts as ____ and Copper acts as ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Anode , Cathode</option><option id="B">Cathode, Anode</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Zn is more reactive than Cu.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Disproportionation reaction is one where same element ____ and ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Gets Oxidized , Gets Reduced</option><option id="B">Reacts with water</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Decomposition of H2O2.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Oxidation number of Manganese in KMnO4 is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">+7</option><option id="B">+4</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>1 + Mn + (-8) = 0.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Oxidation number of Chromium in K2Cr2O7 is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">+6</option><option id="B">+3</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>2 + 2Cr + (-14) = 0.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Oxidation number of Sulfur in H2SO4 is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">+6</option><option id="B">+4</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>2 + S + (-8) = 0.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reducing power of Halide ions increases down the group ____.</text>
            <option id="A">I- &gt; Br- &gt; Cl- &gt; F-</option><option id="B">F- &gt; Cl- &gt; Br- &gt; I-</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Iodide is easily oxidized.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Color change when KMnO4 is reduced in acidic medium? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Purple to Colorless</option><option id="B">Pink to Yellow</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mn+7 (purple) -&gt; Mn+2 (colorless).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Redox titrations use internal or external ____ to detect endpoint.</text>
            <option id="A">Indicators</option><option id="B">Reactants</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Starch for iodine.</explanation></question>
    </easy>
